"Abstract On a snow-sodden, gray in Washington, DC, the media descended on the Supreme Court. It was the high point for the much embattled Communications Decency Act — the case was to be argued at 10 am before the highest court in the United States. Visitors queued up on the plaza in front of the Court as the reporters filed past. From the steps below there were shouts of “Enough is enough” — the slogan of one of the organizations supporting the statute. Amidst a sea of umbrellas, protestors sported signs of “Porn Poisons Our Kids” and “Don't Rape America”."
